{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631450"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:27:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:27:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17374"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17374"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10064"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115215"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10064"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17374"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97223"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7843"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23559"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23563"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115215"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA research team is conducting a study measuring blood pressure in elderly patients. They notice that readings taken in the morning are consistently higher than those taken in the afternoon, even in the same patients. The equipment and measurement technique remain unchanged.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the type of bias present in this study?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Response bias","Recall bias","Selection bias","Measurement bias","Sampling bias"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario demonstrates \u003Cstrong\u003Emeasurement bias\u003C/strong\u003E, where there is systematic variation in the measurement of blood pressure related to the time of day, despite using the same equipment and technique. This represents a systematic error in how the data is being collected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelection bias\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when there are systematic differences in how participants are chosen for a study. \u003Cstrong\u003ERecall bias\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when there are systematic differences in the accuracy or completeness of participants\u0027 memories about past events. \u003Cstrong\u003EResponse bias\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when participants modify their responses based on what they think the researcher wants to hear. \u003Cstrong\u003ESampling bias\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when the sample does not accurately represent the target population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo address measurement bias in this study, the researchers could standardise the timing of measurements, account for natural circadian variations in blood pressure, or potentially implement a randomised schedule for measurements.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Measurement bias occurs when there are systematic errors in how data is collected, recorded, or measured.","Common sources of measurement bias include faulty equipment, inconsistent measurement techniques, and observer variation.","Measurement bias can be reduced through standardisation of procedures, calibration of instruments, and blinding of observers."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97223"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17374"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97223"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T10:06:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T10:06:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10064"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115215"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4948"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T13:30:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"14"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7843"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"M